A strong dependence of the IPs morphology on the powder particle size was observed. Two microstructures predominate in all powder fractions of both alloys (Fig. 2
). The first one denoted by A (Fig. 2a) contains uniformly distributed spheroids of IPs. The second microstructure denoted by B (Fig. 2b) comprises uniformly distributed irregular particles, which are plate-like, star-like and of others shapes. Other microstructures, e.g. colonies (Fig. 2c) or needle-like particles (Fig. 2d) were also found. However, they form only a small part of the powders. In Fig. 3
 the relative appearance of different microstructures is expressed as a function of powder particle size. The microstructure A containing spheroids occupies the majority of the fine particles (25–45μm). The coarse particles (100–125μm) contain mostly irregular IP particles (microstructure B). The finer the powder particle, i.e. the higher the cooling rate, the more IP spheroids are formed. This is valid for both alloys and it will be discussed later in terms of crystallization mechanism.
